rom Attacks, Rules California High Court; Decision comes as violence has become a more regular occurrence on campuses</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>The California Supreme Court ruled Thursday that the University of California can be held liable for failing to protect a student from an attack by a classmate.</Para><Para>The decision, which comes as school shootings have become more regular occurrences across the nation, represents a potential signal that courts expect schools to be increasingly proactive to protect their students.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>"The ground is moving on this," said Gregory Keating, a law professor at the University of Southern California. "The courts are tilting more toward schools needing to protect their students."</Para><Para>The court ruled that a former University of California, Los Angeles, student, who was stabbed by a schizophrenic classmate in 2009, should be able to sue the school for failing to protect her. The decision overturns a ruling by a lower court in 2015 that UCLA had no duty to protect the student.</Para><Para>"Considering the unique features of the college environment, we conclude postsecondary schools do have a special relationship with students while they are engaged in activities that are part of the school's curriculum or closely related to its delivery of educational services," Justice Carol Corrigan wrote in her ruling. "We conclude that violence against students in the classroom or during curricular activities, while rare, is a foreseeable occurrence, and considerations of public policy do not justify categorically barring an injured student's claims against the university."</Para><Para>The case stems from an attack by Damon Thomas on his classmate. Soon after enrolling in 2008, according to court documents, Mr. Thomas began complaining to professors and administrators that other students in his dorm were teasing him. He said if the university failed to discipline the responsible parties the matter would "escalate into a more serious situation."</Para><Para>The school moved Mr. Thomas into another dorm but his complaints continued and faculty began to suspect he was hallucinating, according to court documents. He was soon diagnosed with schizophrenia by a school psychiatrist but he resisted taking his medication.</Para><Para>On Oct. 7, 2009, a professor sent an email to a dean urging that Mr. Thompson receive "urgent outreach." The next day he stabbed Katherine Rosen, a classmate in his chemistry lab, with a kitchen knife in her chest and neck. She survived the attack.</Para><Para>Mr. Thompson ultimately pleaded not guilty by reason of insanity and was diagnosed with paranoid schizophrenia. Ms. Rosen sued the regents of the UCLA along with several school employees for negligence. She argued that UCLA was responsible because colleges have a "special relationship with students in the classroom."</Para><Para>Mr. Keating said the responsibility of colleges to protect students has long been a fuzzy area of the law but the decision signaled recognition that "school shootings are an evermore salient problem and it's creating pressure" to do more to protect students. He pointed out that active shooting drills were becoming more common at schools and that was driven, in part, by legal considerations. If an institution was sued after an incident the drills would be used to show they had tried to take precautions, he said.</Para><Para>"We sympathize with the trauma that Ms. Rosen and her family have endured," said a representative for the school, in a statement. "We are disappointed in the California Supreme Court's decision, and we are also concerned about the decision's potential impact on higher education in California and beyond."</Para><Para>The California Supreme Court ruling may push schools toward being more aggressive in how they handle students with emotional problems, said Stephen Newman, a partner at Stroock &amp; Stroock &amp; Lavan in Los Angeles.</Para><Para>"This is a remarkable decision with extremely broad implications for public schools at all levels," he said in an email.</Para><Para>Write to Douglas Belkin at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:doug.belkin@wsj.com">doug.belkin@wsj.com</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Douglas Belkin </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/schools-have-a-duty-to-protect-students-from-attacks-rules-california-high-court-1521761305" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

